[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/weak_2s"]
[Student "S"]
{You dealt this hand.  

You open with a Weak 2-Bid, 2\D. Partner responds 2NT. What do you say next? 

The 2NT bid is forcing and you have better than a minimum. You show your "feature" by bidding 3\H. Partner now bids 3NT which you naturally pass.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:KQT763.94.KJ7.95 82.AQT.942.JT762 J54.KJ52.AQT3.A8 A9.8763.865.KQ43"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
2S pass 2NT pass 3D pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "6fb90e54191c7b1dde442a02888fc04c0d5ddac02e1ffa7a51072c310608e8c4"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/weak_2s"]
[Student "S"]
{One of the characteristics of Weak 2-Bids is that Responder often is unsure how high to go. That's why the 2NT bid is such a great tool. In this case you bid 2NT and partner says 3\D.  

You weren't sure whether to take partner to game or not. His 3\D bid tells you that he has a 9-11 point opener which includes the \DK. You couldn't hope for much more than that, so you bid 4\S.}

